n","header":"Tythingman 1804, grand juror by 1809","body":"James was made a tythingman of the Kensington church in 1804 at age twenty-six, charged with keeping order during services and reporting Sabbath-breakers. He moved up to grand juror by 1809, a steady ascent through Connecticut's lay civic offices."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"Second wife buried beside her first husband","body":"James married Catherine Morris Dunham in 1842, five years after his first wife Charlotte's death; Catherine had been widowed by James A. Dunham a decade earlier. When she died in 1889 at eighty-nine, she was buried beside Dunham, not James, in South Kensington Cemetery."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Both his sons died unmarried, farming Kensington","body":"James's two sons Charles Bronson and Levi A. lived their whole lives as Kensington farmers and never married, dying in 1859 and 1886. The family's surviving line ran through his daughters Mary Lawrence Botsford and Laura Woodruff Dayton."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM061","plot_notes":"South Burying Ground (South Kensington Cemetery), Kensington, Berlin, Connecticut. James, his first wife Charlotte (Bronson) Cowles, and their two sons Charles and Levi all buried here per Cowles Family Genealogy."},"slug":"james-cowles-1778"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}